                                             ______________|    |____________
                                            |                                |
                        HLD ________________|                                |_________________ LLD

1. High level Desing :                                                                          2. Low level Desgin:
iske ander hum over view of the system ko design krte hai,                                         actual machine coding krni it includes :
Diagram level thinking.                                                                                                               - Classes & objects
- for eg - agr whatsapp design krna hai to kon sa database use kr rhe honge,                                                          - Design patterns (Singleton, Factory)
           message queue ko use krenge,cache etc.                                                                                     - DB schema
- system ke different-different component ko btate hai ki ,                                                                           - API structure
        kis trh se design hoga. isme koi code nhi krna hota. 




                                                               🔥 LOW LEVEL DESIGN 🔥


🔹 Low Level Design ke Types / Components :

                                                       Low Level Design 
                                             ______________|    |____________
                                            |                                |
          Design Principles ________________|                                |_________________ Design Patterns
Design principles developers ko guide krta hai to write clean,                   Design Pattern = common problems ke liye ready-made solutions (templates),
maintainable, reusable, and scalable code.                                       Ye code nahi hota ❌, Ye solution ka idea / structure hota hai ✅.
                                                                                 Design Pattern ka Purpose,Mostly objects ke creation aur interaction ke liye hi hota hai :
🔹 Types of Design Principles 🔹                                                                                                                                   Object kaise banega.
1️⃣ SOLID Principles(Object-Oriented Focused)                                                                                                                       Objects kaise interact karenge.
  Note:- OOP provides the concepts, while SOLID provides the guidelines to use those concepts effectively.                                                          Structure kaise hoga.
        OOP = Tools (hammer, screwdriver) 🔧.
        SOLID = Rules / Engineering knowledge 🧠.
 🔥 Explanation Of SOLID principles :
               S → Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
               O → Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
               L → Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
               I → Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
               D → Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
     🟢 1. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) 
               👉 Ek class ka sirf ek hi kaam hona chahiye.
                     ❌ Galat:
                            class UserService {
                             void saveUser() { }
                             void sendEmail() { }
                            }
                     ✅ Sahi:
                            class UserService {
                             void saveUser() { }
                            }

                            class EmailService {
                             void sendEmail() { }
                            }
     🟢 2. Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
               👉 Code open hona chahiye extension ke liye,
                   but closed hona chahiye modification ke liye.
                   Matlab:
                    Existing code ko change na karo ❌
                    Naya feature add karna ho → new class banao ✅
                     ✅ Ex -
                            interface Payment {
                               void pay();
                            }

                            class CreditCardPayment implements Payment {
                                public void pay() { }
                            }

                            class UpiPayment implements Payment {
                                public void pay() { }
                            }
     🟢 3. Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
               👉 Child class ko parent ki jagah use kar sako bina problem ke.
                     ❌ Galat Example (LSP Break) :
                           👉 Parent class me methods define kiye, lekin child unko properly follow nahi kar raha.
                            class Cat {
                                void drinkMilk() {
                                    System.out.println("Cat drinks milk");
                                }

                                void speak() {
                                    System.out.println("Meow");
                                }
                            }

                            class PetCat extends Cat {
                                @Override
                                void drinkMilk() {
                                    System.out.println("Pet cat drinks milk");
                                }

                                @Override
                                void speak() {
                                    System.out.println("Meow Meow");
                                }
                            }

                            class ToyCat extends Cat {
                                @Override
                                void drinkMilk() {
                                    throw new RuntimeException("Toy cat can't drink milk ❌");
                                }

                                @Override
                                void speak() {
                                    throw new RuntimeException("Toy cat can't speak ❌");
                                }
                            }
                                🔴 Problem kya hai?
                                - ToyCat actually real cat nahi hai
                                - Lekin fir bhi Cat ko extend kar raha hai
                                - Parent ke methods ko properly follow nahi kar raha
                                👉 Agar kahin aisa code ho:
                                                     Cat cat = new ToyCat();
                                                     cat.drinkMilk();  // 💥 Runtime error
                                👉 Matlab:
                                        Child ko parent ki jagah use kiya → program toot gaya ❌, LSP violate ho gaya.
     🟢 4. Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
               👉 Client ko wo methods implement karne ke liye force mat karo jo use nahi chahiye.
                     ❌ Galat:
                            interface Worker {
                                void work();
                                void eat();
                            }

                            class Robot implements Worker {
                                public void work() { }
                                public void eat() { } // useless ❌
                            }
                     ✅ Sahi:
                            interface Workable {
                                void work();
                            }

                            interface Eatable {
                                void eat();
                            }
     🟢 5. Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
               👉 High-level class low-level class pe depend na kare — dono abstraction pe depend karein.
                     ❌ Galat:
                            class Employee {
                                void work() {
                                    System.out.println("Employee working");
                                }
                            }

                            class CEO {
                                Employee emp = new Employee();  // ❌ direct dependency

                                void manage() {
                                    emp.work();
                                }
                            }
                            🔴 Problem:
                            CEO directly Employee pe depend hai ❌
                            Agar kal Employee change hua → CEO ka code bhi change ❌
                            👉 Tight coupling 😵
                     ✅ Sahi:
                            interface Worker {
                                void work();
                            }

                            class Employee implements Worker {
                                public void work() {
                                    System.out.println("Employee working");
                                }
                            }

                            class Manager implements Worker {
                                public void work() {
                                    System.out.println("Manager managing");
                                }
                            }

                            class CEO {
                                Worker worker;   // ✅ abstraction use

                                CEO(Worker worker) {
                                    this.worker = worker;
                                }

                                void manage() {
                                    worker.work();
                                }
                            }
                            ✅ Solution 
                                👉 CEO ab directly Employee pe depend nahi hai
                                👉 CEO sirf Worker (interface) ko jaanta hai
2️⃣ Other Key Principles :
                 DRY → Don’t Repeat Yourself
                                 - Duplicate code avoid karna
                 KISS → Keep It Simple, Stupid
                                 - Complex solutions avoid karo
                 YAGNI → You Aren’t Gonna Need It
                                 - Sirf jo required ho wahi implement karo
                 Composition over Inheritance
                                 - Class behavior ke liye inheritance ki bajaye composition use karo



🔹 Design Patterns ke Types (3 Main Categories) 🔹

          🟢 1. Creational Design Patterns
                    👉 Object kaise banayein (creation logic)
                               Examples:
                                      Singleton
                                      Factory
                                      Abstract Factory
                                      Builder
                                      Prototype
          🟡 2. Structural Design Patterns
                    👉 Objects ko kaise arrange / structure karein
                               Examples:
                                      Adapter
                                      Decorator
                                      Facade
                                      Proxy
                                      Composite
          🔵 3. Behavioral Design Patterns
                    👉 Objects ka behavior & communication kaise hoga
                               Examples:
                                      Observer
                                      Strategy
                                      Command
                                      State
                                      Iterator


                                                                  🔹 Creational Design Pattern 🔹  

🟢 1. Singleton Pattern
👉 Ek hi object poore application me exist kare.
    Use:
        Database connection
        Logger
        Configuration
Ex-

class DBConnection {

    private static DBConnection instance;
    private Connection connection;

    // Private constructor
    private DBConnection() {
        try {
            String url = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb";
            String username = "root";
            String password = "password";

            connection = DriverManager.getConnection(url, username, password);
            System.out.println("Database Connected ✅");

        } catch (SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    // Singleton method
    public static DBConnection getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new DBConnection();
        }
        return instance;
    }

    public Connection getConnection() {
        return connection;
    }
}

 🔹 Singleton ke multiple types (implementations)
  1.1 Early Initialization (Eager Loading)
       👉 Object pehle hi bana diya jata hai (class load hote hi)
Ex - 
class Singleton {
    private static final Singleton instance = new Singleton();

    private Singleton() { }

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        return instance;
    }
}

  1.2 Lazy Initialization (On-Demand)
       👉 Object tab banta hai jab first time zarurat ho
Ex - 
class Singleton {
    private static Singleton instance;

    private Singleton() { }

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}

  1.3 Double-Checked Locking (Best Practical)
Ex - 
class Singleton {
    private static volatile Singleton instance;

    private Singleton() { }

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            synchronized (Singleton.class) {
                if (instance == null) {
                    instance = new Singleton();
                }
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }
}

1.4 Enum Singleton (Most Secure 🔥)
Ex - 
enum Singleton {
    INSTANCE;

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Hello Singleton");
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Access enum singleton
        Singleton singleton = Singleton.INSTANCE;

        singleton.show();   // method call  / or direct way Singleton.INSTANCE.show();
    }
}




🟢 2. Factory Pattern
👉 Object create karne ki responsibility client se hata ke factory class ko de di jati hai.
👉 Client ko exact class ka naam ya creation logic nahi pata hota — wo sirf factory se object maangta hai.
📌 Use Cases:
Jab multiple similar objects create karne ho
Jab object creation complex ho
Jab runtime pe decide karna ho kaunsa object banana hai
Example:
Payment system (UPI / Card / NetBanking)
Notification (Email / SMS / Push)

 🔹 Factory ke multiple types (implementations)

2.1 Simple Factory  :
👉 Ek hi factory class hoti hai jo input ke basis par different objects create karti hai.
👉 ❗ Yaha if-else DIRECT object create karne ke liye use hota hai.
❌ OCP Violation hota hai isme, Kal agar naya type aaye: else if(type.equalsIgnoreCase("WALLET")) {return new WalletPayment();} firse add krna hoga existing code me.
🔸Code - 
1. Common Interface :

interface Payment {
    void pay(double amount);
}

2. Concrete Classes :
class UpiPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Paid " + amount + " using UPI");
    }
}

class CardPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Paid " + amount + " using Card");
    }
}

class NetBankingPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Paid " + amount + " using NetBanking");
    }
}

3. Factory Class ⭐ (Main Part) :
class PaymentFactory {

    public static Payment getPayment(String type) {

        if(type == null) return null;

         // ❗ if-else yaha DIRECT object create kar raha hai
        if(type.equalsIgnoreCase("UPI")) {
            return new UpiPayment();
        } 
        else if(type.equalsIgnoreCase("CARD")) {
            return new CardPayment();
        } 
        else if(type.equalsIgnoreCase("NETBANKING")) {
            return new NetBankingPayment();
        }

        return null;
    }
}

4. Client Code (Use) :
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Payment payment = PaymentFactory.getPayment("UPI");
        payment.pay(1000);

        payment = PaymentFactory.getPayment("CARD");
        payment.pay(2000);
    }
}


2.2 Factory Method Pattern
👉 Har product ke liye alag factory class hoti hai
👉 Object creation subclasses handle karti hain
👉 ❗ Yaha object creation me if-else NAHI hota.
👉 ⚠ Agar if-else hota bhi hai to sirf factory choose karne ke liye hota hai (client side).
✔ OCP follow karta hai
🔸 Code - 
// 1. Product Interface
interface Payment {
    void pay(int amount);
}

// 2. Concrete Products
class UpiPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay(int amount) {
        System.out.println("UPI Payment: " + amount);
    }
}

class CardPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay(int amount) {
        System.out.println("Card Payment: " + amount);
    }
}

// 3. Factory Interface
interface PaymentFactory {
    Payment createPayment();
}

// 4. Concrete Factories
class UpiFactory implements PaymentFactory {
    public Payment createPayment() {
        return new UpiPayment(); // ✔ direct object creation (no if-else)
    }
}

class CardFactory implements PaymentFactory {
    public Payment createPayment() {
        return new CardPayment(); // ✔ direct object creation (no if-else)
    }
}

// 5. Client (Runtime Decision)
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String type = "UPI"; // runtime input

        PaymentFactory factory;

        // ⚠ Yaha if-else sirf factory choose karne ke liye hai
        if(type.equalsIgnoreCase("UPI")) {
            factory = new UpiFactory();
        } 
        else if(type.equalsIgnoreCase("CARD")) {
            factory = new CardFactory();
        } 
        else {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid type");
        }

        // ✔ Actual object creation subclass me ho raha hai
        Payment payment = factory.createPayment();
        payment.pay(1000);
    }
}


2.3 Abstract Factory Pattern
👉 Ye Factory Method ka next level hai
👉 Ek factory → multiple related objects create karti hai (family of objects)
👉 ✔ OCP follow karta hai
👉 ✔ Highly scalable
🔸 Code - 
// 1. Payment Interface
interface Payment {
    void pay(int amount);
}

// 2. Notification Interface
interface Notification {
    void send();
}

// 3. Concrete Payment Classes
class UpiPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay(int amount) {
        System.out.println("UPI Payment: " + amount);
    }
}

class CardPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay(int amount) {
        System.out.println("Card Payment: " + amount);
    }
}

// 4. Concrete Notification Classes
class SmsNotification implements Notification {
    public void send() {
        System.out.println("SMS Sent");
    }
}

class EmailNotification implements Notification {
    public void send() {
        System.out.println("Email Sent");
    }
}

// 5. Abstract Factory
interface AbstractFactory {
    Payment createPayment();
    Notification createNotification();
}

// 6. Concrete Factories
class UpiFactory implements AbstractFactory {

    public Payment createPayment() {
        return new UpiPayment();
    }

    public Notification createNotification() {
        return new SmsNotification();
    }
}

class CardFactory implements AbstractFactory {

    public Payment createPayment() {
        return new CardPayment();
    }

    public Notification createNotification() {
        return new EmailNotification();
    }
}

// 7. Client (Runtime Decision with if-else)
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String type = "UPI"; // runtime input (user/API/db)

        AbstractFactory factory;

        // ✔ if-else sirf factory choose karne ke liye hai
        if(type.equalsIgnoreCase("UPI")) {
            factory = new UpiFactory();
        } 
        else if(type.equalsIgnoreCase("CARD")) {
            factory = new CardFactory();
        } 
        else {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid type");
        }

        // ✔ Object creation factories ke andar ho raha hai
        Payment payment = factory.createPayment();
        Notification notification = factory.createNotification();

        payment.pay(1000);
        notification.send();
    }
}


